de.feig.FEDM.Core

Class IAsyncGroup

  • java.lang.Object
    • de.feig.FEDM.Core.IAsyncGroup

  • public class IAsyncGroup
extends java.lang.Object
    Internal class providing methods for asynchronous communication.
    Description:
    This class realizes the nested interface with special methods for asynchronous communication for the Reader class ReaderModule.
    Methods of this class can be called with the IAsync member of ReaderModule.

      • startNotificationTask

        public void startNotificationTask(int portNumber,
                                  INotificationListener listener,
                                  boolean withAck)
                           throws java.lang.Exception,
                                  FeException
        Method to start an internal listener task for notifications sent by one Reader, which must work in Notification-Mode
        Parameters:
        portNumber - TCP-Port, which listens for notifications
        listener - Listener object, which must be derived from INotificationListener
        withAck - when true, an acknowledge protocol is sent to the Reader, when the listener method of INotificationListener is finished
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - exception thrown in JNI layer
        FeException - exception with error code (<0)

        Description:
        A recurring task of applications is inventorying transponders in the antenna field of the reader. Ideally this should run in the background and then tell the application when transponders are in the field or when the notification has arrived. This is precisely the functionality you can implement using the startNotificationTask method.
        Internally a thread is started which waits for the reply protocol of the reader and provides the reply data to the application using the call of a listener method of interface INotificationListener. A task should only be started if the Notification-Mode is integrated and activated in the Reader's firmware. Only TCP/IP communication is supported.
        The task waits for reception of the Buffered Read Mode data and then invokes one of the listener methods. After the method returns, data can immediately be received again by the Reader.
        If no error occurs, the response data are collected in the internal Buffered Read Mode Table and must be requested gradually with IBrmTableGroup.getItemByIndex(int).
        In case of transmission errors the listener method is invoked with the error code and the receiving procedure then resumed. If the Keep-Alive option is activated (default setting: activated), then the listener socket is closed automatically after a break of the network cable or after loss of power and is recovered again. This ensures the reliability of the network connection.
        The timing for closing the socket by Keep-Alive is calculated by the formula:
        IdleTime + RepeatCount * IntervalTime
        where the default settings are:
        - IdleTime is 500ms
        - RepeatCount is 5 (Linux, Window XP) or 10 (Windows Vista or higher)
        - IntervalTime is 500ms

        Notes
        • Depending on the Reader setting, large quantities of data may be sent by the Reader in very short time intervals. Without use of a handshake procedure (see system manual for the Reader), data may be lost if the host is not appropriate for the quantity of notifications.
        • For Windows systems: check the settings of the Firewall, if notifications are not received.

      • startInventoryTask

        public void startInventoryTask(byte timeout,
                               IInventoryListener listener,
                               boolean repetitive)
                        throws java.lang.Exception,
                               FeException
        Method to execute a single or repetitive asynchronous Inventory (only for some IDENTIFICATION Reader)
        Parameters:
        timeout - Timeout (in multiple of 100ms) for waiting for the response
        listener - Listener object, which must be derived from IInventoryListener
        repetitive - when true, a repetitive Inventory task is created and continued after each response with triggerInventoryTask()
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - exception thrown in JNI layer
        FeException - exception with error code (<0)

        Description:
        The Inventory command is sent to the Reader and the internal thread waits for the transponder response or a timeout.
        NOTE: The task in the Reader cannot be canceled nor any other command can be sent to the Reader until the task is finished.

      • setKeepAlivePara

        public int setKeepAlivePara(boolean enableKeepAlive,
                            int keepAliveIdleTime,
                            int keepAliveProbeCount,
                            int keepAliveIntervalTime)
        Method to adjust the keep-alive parameters for notification listener tasks
        Parameters:
        enableKeepAlive - if true, keep alive option will be enabled
        keepAliveIdleTime - wait time in ms for first probe after connection is dropped down (For Linux: time is rounded up to seconds)
        keepAliveProbeCount - Linux: number of probes. For Windows Server 2003, 2000 and XP it is fixed to 5 by Microsoft. For Windows Vista and later it is fixed to 10 by Microsoft.
        keepAliveIntervalTime - wait time in ms between probes
        Returns:
        if successful (=0) or error code (<0)
        Description:
        The keep-alive option is enabled by default and can be adjusted with this method. The parameters are used with the next call of startInventoryTask(byte, de.feig.FEDM.Core.IInventoryListener, boolean).
        Keep-alive parameters of a running task cannot be adjusted.
        Kepp-alive is enabled by default with the following settings:
        Keep-alive Idle Time = 500ms
        Keep-alive Probe Count = 5 (only for Linux)
        Keep-alive Interval Time = 500ms

        NOTE: Parameters must be set in front of the call of startNotificationTask().
